SIMPLE: sensual
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sensual
<hw>Sen"su*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>sensualis</ets>, from <ets>sensus</ets> sense: cf. F.
<ets>sensuel</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Pertaining to, consisting
in, or affecting, the sense, or bodily organs of perception; relating
to, or concerning, the body, in distinction from the spirit.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Pleasing and <qex>sensual</qex> rites and ceremonies.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Far as creation's ample range extends,⟦br⟧
The scale of <qex>sensual</qex>, mental powers ascends.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, not spiritual or intellectual; carnal;
fleshly; pertaining to, or consisting in, the gratification of the
senses, or the indulgence of appetites; wordly.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These be they who separate themselves, <qex>sensual</qex>, having
not the Spirit.</q> <rj><qau>Jude 19.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The greatest part of men are such as prefer . . . that good which
is <qex>sensual</qex> before whatsoever is most divine.</q>
<rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Devoted to the pleasures of sense and appetite;
luxurious; voluptuous; lewd; libidinous.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No small part of virtue consists in abstaining from that wherein
<qex>sensual</qex> men place their felicity.</q>
<rj><qau>Atterbury.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Pertaining or peculiar to the philosophical doctrine
of sensualism.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sensualism</ent>⟦br⟧
